Currently advertise only retry for timeout error and protocol error. But when autobahn restarts, tchannel will stop advertising.  Create a large range of exception for retry for now to keep tchannel app alive. This can avoid keep updating current on-boarding service.

That's also what Node does.

Discovered while trying to get a response for @hamsal on gitter (ping'ed by @willingc):

```
What are my options if the autosave is not happening as frequently as I want? even if I set %autosave 15 it seems to only be happening on the order of minutes
I also used IPython.notebook.minimum_autosave_interval = 15000; and it was still not happening except every few minutes
```

To whom I'll respond that the autosave frequency depends on how long it takes to save the notebook, you canot save more often than the time to upload a notebook. And the correct way to change the notebook minimal save time would be the following :  

```js
// ~/.jupyter/custom/custom.js
define(['base/js/namespace', 'base/js/events'], function(Jupyter, events){
    events.on("notebook_loaded.Notebook", function () {
        // Anything below 5000 will disbale autosave on < 4.2
        Jupyter.notebook.minimum_autosave_interval = 15000; 
    });
});
```

Lots of cool stuff in here, but the biggest change is the way articles and embedded items are being stored. Instead of being just HTML, an article is now represented by a JSON array -- something like this:
```javascript
var content = {
    "Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit. Pellentesque eu ligula in eros elementum luctus eget nec purus. ",
    {
        type: "image",
        data: {
            caption: "This is a caption",
                image: {
                    id: 9,
                    url: "http://url.to.some/image.jpg",  
                }
        }
    },
    "Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit. Pellentesque eu ligula in eros elementum luctus eget nec purus. ",
    "Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit. Pellentesque eu ligula in eros elementum luctus eget nec purus. ",
}
```

This makes it a lot easier to manage embedded items (which are represented as simple objects) in both the front-end and back-end. For saving in particular, all Dispatch has to do is parse the content, pick out the embedded items and save each one -- no more of that shortcode crap.

Same goes for the front-end and mobile consumers -- embedded items are easier to find and render.

